# Changelog Maintenance

`CHANGELOG.md` must be kept up to date as the codebase evolves. Follow the [Keep a Changelog](https://keepachangelog.com/en/1.1.0/) format strictly.

## File Location

`CHANGELOG.md` lives in the project root: `/CHANGELOG.md`

## When to Add an Entry

Add a changelog entry for these commit types:

| Commit Type | Changelog? | Category |
|-------------|-----------|----------|
| `feat` | **Yes** | Added |
| `fix` | **Yes** | Fixed |
| `refactor` (breaking) | **Yes** | Changed |
| `perf` | **Yes** | Changed |
| `feat` (removing) | **Yes** | Removed |
| `deprecate` | **Yes** | Deprecated |
| `security` | **Yes** | Security |
| `refactor` (non-breaking) | Only if user-visible | Changed |
| `docs` | No (unless major) | -- |
| `style` | No | -- |
| `chore` | No (unless user-visible) | -- |
| `test` | No | -- |
| `ci` | No | -- |

## Entry Format

Each entry is a single concise line under the appropriate category heading:

```markdown
- <Action verb> <what changed> (`<primary file or module>`)
```

**Good examples:**
```markdown
- Add NumPyro NUTS adapter for Bayesian MCMC calibration (`calibration/numpyro_adapter.py`)
- Fix Sacramento UZTWM parameter bounds to match literature range (1, 300) (`models/sacramento.py`)
- Remove SPOTPY dependency in favour of vendored SCE-UA (`calibration/sceua_adapter.py`)
```

**Bad examples:**
```markdown
- Updated stuff
- Fixed bug
- Changes to calibration module
```

## File Structure

```markdown
# Changelog

All notable changes to **pyrrm** are documented in this file.
The format follows [Keep a Changelog](https://keepachangelog.com/en/1.1.0/).

---

## [Unreleased]

### Added
- ...

### Changed
- ...

### Fixed
- ...

### Removed
- ...

---

## [X.Y.Z] - YYYY-MM-DD

### Added
- ...

---

[Unreleased]: https://github.com/ACTGovernment/ACT-Rainfall-Runoff-Modelling/compare/vX.Y.Z...HEAD
[X.Y.Z]: https://github.com/ACTGovernment/ACT-Rainfall-Runoff-Modelling/releases/tag/vX.Y.Z
```

## Rules

1. **Always add to `[Unreleased]`** -- never directly to a versioned section
2. **Use the correct category**: Added, Changed, Deprecated, Removed, Fixed, Security
3. **One entry per logical change** -- don't combine unrelated changes
4. **Action verbs**: Add, Remove, Fix, Change, Deprecate, Improve, Replace, Update
5. **Include file/module reference** in backtick-parentheses at end of entry
6. **Chronological order** within each category -- newest entries at the bottom
7. **No duplicate entries** -- check existing entries before adding

## Version Bumping

When cutting a release:

1. Change `## [Unreleased]` to `## [X.Y.Z] - YYYY-MM-DD`
2. Add a new empty `## [Unreleased]` section above it
3. Update the comparison links at the bottom of the file
4. Update the version in `pyproject.toml` to match
5. Commit as: `chore: release vX.Y.Z`

## Versioning Guidelines

- **Major** (X.0.0): Breaking API changes
- **Minor** (0.X.0): New features, new models, new calibration methods
- **Patch** (0.0.X): Bug fixes, documentation, performance improvements
